<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-07-11T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-07-11T18:00:00-05:00" n="931" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d931">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">823.00 Revolutions/330: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Chargé in Peru</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BWC1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Burdett</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-07-11T19:00:00-04:00">July 11,
                                    1932—7 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>31. Your 100, July 9, 4 p.m. Department understands from Navy Department
                            that Chief of the Naval Mission advised the Peruvian authorities that
                            their request should be transmitted through the Peruvian Embassy in
                            Washington. Department therefore will not take any action unless and
                            until the matter is taken up by the Peruvian Embassy here.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>